@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqua_data_grp" "Aquarium Data"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
These gadgets contain data of the current ( loaded ) aquarium
which were specified when it was created, they are:

- Name of the aquarium - Date of Creation - Owner ( or Creator ) - Number of Liters contained in the aquarium
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqua_env_O2_txt" "O2 Text"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Number of milligrams per liter of O2 present in the aquarium.
There should be enough O2 before lights are switched off because
vegetals will start consuming O2 as fishes do and will stop production
of it. When lights are switched on there should be about 2.0-4.0
milligrams per liter of O2 to ensure fishes life and bacteria
action ( if Filter is present ) O2, as CO2, is also exchanged
with outer environment trying to reach equilibrium, O2 concetration
of outer environment is defined as the O2 concentration in new water
when you exchange water.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqua_env_CO2_txt" "CO2 Text"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Number of milligrams per liter of CO2 present in aquarium water.
This element is very important because is used to maintain a certain
Ph in some water hardness conditions. Infact when water is too tender
( DH low ) with a small alteration in CO2 concentration Ph can vary
over a wide range, so it's better have a medium hard water
( see @{"Water Hardness" LINK "aqua_env_DH_txt" } ). CO2 is also
important in the oxigen production cycle: vegetals, when light is on,
produce O2 and use CO2. CO2, as O2, is also exchanged with outer
environment trying to reach equilibrium, CO2 concetration of outer
environment is defined as the CO2 concentration in new water when
you exchange water.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqua_env_NH3_txt" "NH3 Text"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Number of milligrams per liter of NH3 present in aquarium water.
This element, like NH4+, is produced by fishes and food when is
not eaten and goes bad; this element is very dangerous and it
shouldn't never be more than 0.1 milligrams per liter.
See @{"Filter" LINK "instr_filter" } for information on how to
eliminate it ( transform ).
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqua_env_NH4_txt" "NH4 Text"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Number of milligrams per liter of NH4+ present in aquarium water.
This element, like NH3, is produced by fishes and food when is not
eaten and goes bad; this element is very dangerous and it shouldn't
never be more than 0.1 milligrams per liter.
See @{"Filter" LINK "instr_filter" } for information on how to
eliminate it ( transform ).
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqua_env_NO2_txt" "NO2 Text"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Number of milligrams per liter of NO2 present in aquarium water.
This element derives from NH3 and NH4+ and is produced by bacteria
present into the filter; it is not dangerous like NH3 and NH4+ but
its concentration should never more than 10 milligrams per liter.
Filter transforms this element in NO3- ( see @{"Filter" LINK "instr_filter" } ).
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqua_env_NO3_txt" "NO3 Text"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Number of milligrams per liter of NO3- present in aquarium water.
Derives from NO2 and is better tolerated by fishes which can handle
this element until 200 milligrams per liter. To eliminate this element
water must be changed from times to times. See @{"Filter" LINK "instr_filter" }
for information about the whole transformation cycle.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqua_env_DH_txt" "DH Text"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
°DH (German Degrees) : they measure water hardness and a single
degree means 17.9 milligrams per liter of CACO3. This element
should be kept in a desired range considering fishes needs but
it should never too low because a change in CO2 concentration means
a change in Ph and the more high is hardness the more CO2 concentration
should vary to change Ph.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqua_env_PH_txt" "PH Text"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Ph measures the acidity of water, the more it is low the more water
is acid; this value can be changed adjusting CO2 concentration considering
water hardness and should be maintained in the range needed by fishes in
our aquarium, but usually a acid-neutral water (6.0-7.0) is a good value.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqua_env_temp_ga" "Temperature Gauge"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Temperature in degrees Centrigrade, this should be mantained near the
values needed by fishes in our aquarium. Consider that if a thermostat
is not present Temperature moves toward outer environment Temperature
which is, by default, indicated in the temperature of new water when
you change water.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqua_speed_sli" "Simulation Speed Slider"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
This Slider can be used to define simulation speed, to see how this
really affect speed see Preferences/@{"Update Kind" LINK "prefs_updatekind_rad" }.
Of course the bigger the number you select more speed you'll gain in
system simulation. To stop system updating select 0 with the slider.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqua_env_update_txt" "Update Text"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
This text will tell you when the internal simulation engine is updating
the system. To know more about this see @{"Sytem Updating" LINK "System Updating" }.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "fish_infowin_chk" "Fish Info Window Check"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
This checkmark defines if the Fish Info Windows is opened or not.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "fish_list" "Fish List"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
This list contains the names of the fishes in aquarium, selecting
one of them some informations will be displayed in the Fish Info Window,
if opened, and the energy of the fish will be shown in the right gauge.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "fishload_but" "Fish Load"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Opens a new requester so that a new fish can be loaded into aquarium.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "fishrem_but" "Fish Remove"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
If a fish in the list is selected removes it from aquarium and move
it back to the fridge ( see @{"Frozen Fishes Directory" LINK "Frozen Fished Directory" } ).
@ENDNODE

@NODE "fishname_str" "Fish Name"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Name of the selected fish, write in a new name to rename fish.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "energy_ga" "Fish Energy Gauge"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
This gauge shows selected fish energy, when 0 fish is dead.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "fishcheck_grp" "Fish Animation Checks"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
These checks can be used to show or hide the selected fish, to
let it move or stop it, and to make it solid or to let it be passed
through by other fishes or objects. This checks should not be used
to have a (real) simulation but can be useful for some testing
( will be removed in the future ).
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqobj_infowin_chk" "Object Info Window Check"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
This checkmark defines if the Object Info Windows is opened or not.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqobj_lights_chk" "Light Switcher"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
This Checkmark is the light switcher. It is disabled when autolighter
is on ( see @{"Automation Prefs" LINK "Automation Prefs" } )
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqobj_list" "Object List"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
This list mantains loaded object names. You can can select an item
to get information about it through the right panel or through the
information window, if opened.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqobjload_but" "Object Load"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Open a requester to load a new object.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqobjname_str" "Object Name"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Name of the selected object, write in a new string to change the
selected object name.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqobj_switch_chk" "Object OnOff"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Switch on or off if not disabled ( object always on ).
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqobj_setting_but" "Object Settings"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
If not disabled let the user open the settings window about the
selected object.

Currently supported adjustable objects are:

@{" Filter        " LINK "instr_filter" }
@{" CO2 Inhalator " LINK "aqua_env_CO2_txt" }
@{" O2 Inhalator  " LINK "aqua_env_O2_txt" }
@{" Thermostat    " LINK "instr_thermo" }
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqobj_prodcons_grp" "Group"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Production, per iteration, of O2 and CO2 by the selected object.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqobj_age_ga" "Object Age"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Age of the object in iteration, when the max number of iterations
( max age in Info Window ) are reached usually the object permorfs
its task in a wrong manner ( for examples inhalate less CO2 than requested );
it should be removed and a new one should be loaded in its place.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqobj_dirty_ga" "Object Dirty"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
This is mainly for filter objects. See @{"Filter" LINK "instr_filter" }
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqobj_temp_ga" "Object Temperature"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
This is only for Thermostat object. See @{"Thermostat" LINK "instr_thermo" }
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqobjcheck_grp" "Group"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
These checks can be used to show or hide the selected object,
to let it move or stop it, and to make it solid or to let it
be passed through by other fishes or objects. This checks should
not be used to have a (real) simulation but can be useful for some
testing ( will be removed in the future ).
@ENDNODE

@NODE "swap_scr_but" "Swap Screens"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
This button shows your aquarium. See @{"Animation Screen" LINK "Animation Screen" }
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqua_refresh_but" "Refresh System"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Force system updating. See @{"System Updating" LINK "System Updating" }
@ENDNODE

@NODE "prefs_win" "Preferences"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
                        @{" Update Kind      " LINK "prefs_updatekind_rad" }
                        @{" Fish Update Kind " LINK "prefs_updatefish_grp" }
                        @{" External Viewer  " LINK "prefs_viewer_grp" }
                        @{" Show Names Font  " LINK "prefs_font_pop" }
			@{" Fast Update      " LINK "prefs_fastupdate_chk" }
@ENDNODE

@NODE "prefs_fastupdate_chk" "Fast Update"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
You can decide if after loading your aquarium animation and interface
interaction must be stopped to update system ( this is usually fast )
or if update iterations must be done while animating and interact.
If many hours are passed from last time you saved maybe it's better to
have this check enabled and to use fastupdate.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "prefs_updatekind_rad" "Update Kind"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
This Gadget helps you selecting the way fast update happens.
Selecting More Iterations means that after a 7.5 mins the system
will be updated more than once simulating time passing faster.
Selecting Shorter Delay means that time between system updates
will be shorter. To adjust the number of iteration or how many
times you must divide 7.5 mins to have another iteration you can
use the Simulation Speed Slider.

If you want to force update you can use the Refresh Button.

See @{"System Updating" LINK "System Updating" }
@ENDNODE

@NODE "prefs_updatefish_grp" "Fish Update Kind"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
You can use this checkmarks to define how fish status is updated.

Weighted Hit:

Selecting this option enables calculation of a new fish status
using a weight for each kind of element kept in consideration.
This means that is, for example, water Ph is out of bounds considering
a particular fish Ph range this fact will subtract some energy
points to fish data considering the "Weight" of Ph against
other elements such as Temperature Dh or any other thing you
can read in the Water Status Window.

Offset Hit: This option lets you decide how many energy points must
be subracted to a fish when element goes out of bounds;
in other words when this option is off a defined amount of
points are subtracted for each out of bounds situation,
when this option is on the number of points depend on how
much we are out of bounds.

N.B.

You can adjust weights and default out of bounds subtracted
energy points:
see @{"Changing System Updating" LINK "Changing System Updating" }
@ENDNODE

@NODE "prefs_viewer_grp" "External Viewer"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
You can decide to use an external viewer to show info pictures, just turn on the checkmark and chose a program ( your viewer ) with the file requester. If you turn on the checkmark but you don't select a viewer or it cannot be found the internal IFF viewer is used.

The last checkmark enable loading of IFF images in fast ram.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "prefs_font_pop" "Show Names Font"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Chose the font which will be used when displaying names of objects in animation screen. If font couldn't be loaded Topaz is used.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "create_win" "Aquarium Creation Window"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
                        @{" Creation Name   " LINK "create_name_str" }
                        @{" Creation Date   " LINK "create_date_str" }
                        @{" Creation Owner  " LINK "create_owner_str" }
                        @{" Creation Liters " LINK "create_water_sli" }
@ENDNODE

@NODE "create_name_str" "Creation Name"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Name of the new aquarium your about to create.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "create_date_str" "Creation Date"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Date Of Creation, should be today in you preferred format.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "create_owner_str" "Creation Owner"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Your Name or your Nickname, this is the name of the aquarium creator
( and of its owner of course ).
@ENDNODE

@NODE "create_water_sli" "Creation Liters"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Defines the number of liters contained in your new aquarium.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "water_select_sli" "Water Percentage"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Use this slider to define the percentage of water to substitute:
each number is a ten percent of new water which enters the aquarium.
In the gauges you can read the exact amount of new and old water in liters.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "water_new_grp" "New Water Elements"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
These are elements in milligrams per liter present in new water and
which will be mixed, depending on how much water you exchange, with
those already present in aquarium water. Remember that in new water
there are not NH3, NH4+, NO2 and NO3-. You can change new water element
quantities, to know how see: @{"New Water Prefs" LINK "AQUAWC.prefs" }
@ENDNODE

@NODE "water_old_grp" "Group"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
These are the concentration of elements in current aquarium water.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "water_final_grp" "Group"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
This is the final water situation depending on new and old water
element concentrations and on how these waters are mixed together.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "auto_feed_switch_chk" "Autofeeder Check"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Switch on and off autofeeder
@ENDNODE

@NODE "auto_feed_sli" "Autofood Slider"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Defines how much time should pass between feeding fishes ( In hours ).
Feeding is performed loading some food which is a particular kind of
object, after it is loaded it provides some food and is removed
automatically from the aquarium; if is not eaten it goes bad and
produces NH3 and NH4+ so do not feed your fishes too often.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "auto_food_txt" "Food Kind"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Food to be loaded after defined time is passed.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "auto_light_switch_chk" "Autolighter Check"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Switch on and off autolighter.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "auto_lighton_sli" "Lights On Slider"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Defines how many hours light should be kept on. If 0 and hours
during which light should be off are 0 then, by default, means
light always on.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "auto_lightoff_sli" "Lights Off Slider"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Defines how many hours light should be kept off after they've
been on as defined with lights on slider.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "filter_val_sli" "Filter Settings"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Define how much dirtiness is present on the filter. You can
of course clean it by reducing dirtiness.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "co2inalator_val_sli" "CO2 Inhalator Settings"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Defines how much CO2 should be inhalated into aquarium by
inhalator. This must be on to work.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "o2inalator_val_sli" "O2 Inhalator Settings"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Defines how much O2 is inhalated into aquarium. This object must
be on to work.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "thermo_val_sli" "Temperature Settings"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Set the desired temperature of water. Again this object must
be on to work.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqwin_show_but" "Show Object"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Load, if defined, a picture showing selected object.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqwin_maxage_txt" "Max Age"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Max number of iterations of this object before it is too old
to work properly.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aqwin_autoremove_txt" "Autoremove"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
If autoremove is Yes means then when max age is reached ( max
number of iteration to consider the object very old ) object
is automatically removed from aquarium. It is used mainly in food.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "fishwin_show_but" "Show Fish"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Load, if defined, a picture showing selected fish.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "fishwin_showdata_chk" "Other Data"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Show other fish data.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "fishwin_birth_grp" "Day of birth"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Day of birth for this fish.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "fishwin_birth_maxage_txt" "Fish Max Age"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
 Max age for this kind of fish.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "fishwin_ranges_grp" "Ranges"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
These are the typical ranges for the selected fish, you should
respect them if you want your fish live enough to enjoy its beauty.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "instr_filter" "Filter"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Filter is very important in aquaria since it is the only thing
which can protect fishes by intoxication by dangerous elements
such as NH3 and NH4+ ( but NO2 And NO3- too ), so it must always
be clean ( but not too much, see below ) to work properly.
Fishes produce NH3 and NH4+ with urea and other, and food to may
go bad and raise the concentration of these two elements in water.
Fishes should resist until a concentration of about 0.1 milligrams
of NH3 or NH4+ per liter and so it's easy to run into bad situation.
Filter solve this problem using bacteria which transform NH3 and NH4+
in NO2 less toxic ( until 10 milligrams per liter ). This element is
then transformed, by other bacteria, in NO3- which is well tolerated
( until 150-200 milligrams per liter ); this last element must be
eliminated with periodical water substitution. As time passes filter
gets dirty and should be cleaned periodically so to make it fully work,
but cleaning it means killing some of the bacteria so useful in water
cleaning, so you should never clean your filter too much ( since cleaning
a filter means reducing the amount of dirtiness you should let your filter
be at least 40-45 dirty to let bacteria continue their work without problems ).
@ENDNODE

@NODE "instr_thermo" "Thermostat"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
This is useful to keep water at a certain temperature and must be used
considering fishes needs
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Animation Screen" "Animation Screen"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"

Animation screen is a double buffered screen which show your
aquarium, it can be reached by pressing a button on the main Aquarium
Simulator window or simply pressing SPACE when this window is
active.
To get back to the control window you can press again SPACE or click
the right mouse button.
(This screen switching idea was taken from Torsten Klein's ASpringies,
thank you Torsten ).
Pressing the left mouse button should continue a stopped animation
dued usually by printing of object names on screen.
To get these names appear you should select Show Names in menu when
in the control window or when in animation screen by pressing the
RETURN key ( this only "flashes" the screen with names, so keep it
pressed to make names follow their respective objects ).
Using cursor keys rotate point of view around axes:
left and right ( y axis )
left and right + shift ( z axis )
up and down ( x axis )

This can sometimes get hard to handle so pressing HELP will
put point of view in its original position.

To zoom in press Q, to zoom out press Z.

See @{"Animation Prefs" LINK "Animation Prefs" }

@ENDNODE

@NODE "System Updating" "System Updating"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"

Fishes and objects data need to be update from time to time, in particular
an iteration of the system is performed after 7.5 mins.
Another situation when updating the system is needed is when you save
your aquarium and you reload it after some time, for example a day.

The problem that appear during system updating is that a lot of time
could be necessary to handle the environment variables, fishes and
objects, especially if a lot of them are present in your aquarium.

This is also more evident after a long time you waited before reloading
your aquarium, a lot of iterations must be performed to reach current
day, and this means a lot of waiting time before starting working
with your aquarium.

My personal solution was to create an incremental updating function,
this means that updating is not performed in a single step but that
all the data are touched in different moments so to reduce the
amount of waiting time for the user and in particular to avoid
interruption in interface communication ( MUI ) and in 3D graphics
animation.

Of course some gadgets are disabled during system updating, to
avoid modifications of some variables while handling them.

If you have other ideas tell me : @{"Author" LINK "Author" }

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Frozen Fishes Directory" "Frozen Fishes Directory"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
Under AQUA: there is an important directory which contain fishes
of different species.
When you load an object a copy of it is made in your aquarium directory,
when you load a fish you really take a fish from somewhere, in
particular our fridge ( Frozen-Fishes Dir ), and put it in another
place, this means that the fish data file is not only copied but
really moved from a place on disk to another.
When updating the system this and other files are rewritten, and
when you remove a fish from your aquarium you replace it in
its original directory, which is usually a subdir in Frozen-Fishes.
This means that this subdir must be expressed in your file, see
@{"Writing New Fishes" LINK "Writing New Fishes" } or the fish will be simply replaced
in Frozen-Fishes dir.

NOTE: When you remove dead fishes, like any other, they will keep
their state forever ( unless you manually edit these files ).

NOTE: A particular archive is provided so to have a backup of all
fishes. See @{" File Management And AQUA: Structure " LINK "Files" }

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Animation Prefs" "Animation Prefs"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"

When you change screen mode or when you load a new palette two particular
files are used to save these informations:

S:3DSysStd.scr...Animation Screen Mode Information
S:3DSysStd.pal...Animation Screen Palette

NOTE: As you can see these files are saved in S: directory

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Automation Prefs" "Automation Prefs"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"

When you reload a previously saved aquarium passed time is calculated so
to update your aquarium, it may then happen that for a long time you
can leave the aquairum alone ( not for too much, you should take
a look at it every day ) and of course some things should be done to
keep the aquarium in good conditions almost everyday, or even more than
once in a day. For example you should provide some food to your fishes
at least two times a day ( it depends on how many fishes are in the
aquarium and on how much food you load into aquarium everytime you
feed your fishes ).
To do it automatically you can select Automation Prefs in Menu and
decide to turn on autofeeder spcificating how much time must pass
among feedings and what food to load everytime has passed.
You can also switch on a machine which keeps on the light for some
hours and then keeps it off for some time ( these time intervals can
be defined using two separated sliders ).

@ENDNODE


@NODE "Changing System Updating" "Changing System Updating"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
You can change system behaviour in many ways :

                        @{"Changing Updating Constants" LINK "Changing Updating Constants" }
                        @{"Writing New Fishes" LINK "Writing New Fishes" }
                        @{"Writing New Objects" LINK "Writing New Objects" }
@ENDNODE

