@NODE "Introduction" "Introduction"
@TOC "MAIN"

@{"Skip Main Introduction" LINK "Introduction" 32}

                                                        13th, May 1995

Sometimes ago, we where in September 1994, a new project for the "SISTEMI I"
exam was proposed : Simulate an aquarium on your computers.
It seemed very interesting and I and a friend of mine decided to work
together and build a simple but complete program based on this project.
As stated in the table of contents this project was proposed by our
professor Roberto Polillo, who saw a program called AquaZone ( all rights
of this program are copyright of the authors and publishers of it )
on some Macs during an exposition in the U.S.A. ( if I'm not wrong ).
This program simulates a colorful and realistic aquarium, it has digitized
graphics and seemed to handle realistically all simulation details
( I had only a fast and simple look at it ).
Time passed I had some family problems and it was the beginning of
January when we saw that nothing was done.
Since my friend has not a computer we decided to work on machines in
our lab at school, but it is almost impossible if you don't get a place
early in the morning and since we had to follow other courses it was
impossible to have a line of code written for almost 4 months.
Here I decided that it was better working at home, with more time
and knowledge of the machine...Amiga.
From that moment I've not seen my friend almost anymore so I decided
( or better I was forced to decide ) that I had to work alone.
Then I also decided that with old ECS chipset, with no scanner, and
with not great painters it was almost impossible to get some good
bitmap graphics so I started working on some simple 3D routines which
ended in March in my 3DSystem library ( a link library ).
Using this library and MUI 2.0 by Stefan Stuntz I started working on
3D Aquarium Simulator.

3D Aquarium Simulator uses 3D graphics to show fishes and objects
appearance in a virtual world created by the user.
Infact using 3D graphics results in giving the oppurtunity to
all users of making their own graphics ( which I like to see if
you create any : see @{" Bugs And Suggestions " LINK "Bugs" } ).
Of course graphics is not as coloured and beautiful like that of
AquaZone or of any bitmap oriented program, but I always liked
the opportunity to move in the virtual world we are creating and
I also think that when someone sees an aquarium the first thing
he does is to go nearer and turn around the aquarium to have some
different views of the same micro world.

Apart from graphics the most important aspect of this simulation
is that it try to consider many ( not all ) the aspect of life
in a complex microcosm where different form of life live together.

The idea is that many of the constants ( which become variables )
in the simulation can be changed modifying some simple files,
so that we can experiment which values provide a more realistic
simulation. The biggest problem is that I didn't know very
much of aquaria, of fishes, and many other thing, so I apologize
to all you aquaria experts for my coarse mistakes since now.
Please if you can help me giving me ideas ( and solutions )
you are welcome see again @{" Bugs And Suggestions " LINK "Bugs" } for information on
how to reach me.

The program is built in a way that helps you in making experiments,
not creating a real aquarium, and in building and mantaining a real
aquarium : this means that if you load fishes and objects but
you have not defined an aquarium before you can do everything you
want and nothing will be saved to fix your decisions and actions.

To build an aquarium you must select New from the main menu, then
after you filled in some data you can add fishes and objects to
your aquarium; when you quit your aquarium will be saved because
fishes and object status is always updated, if you reload your
aquarium after some time it will be updated to show the situation
after this pause.

An iteration of the system is performed after 7.5 mins even if you
can speed up the simulation.

Fishes have their own needs, temperature, Ph, and so on, so
you should respect them if you want your little friends to live
happily; to do so some objects must be loaded and turned on:
a filter, o2 and co2 inhalators in needed, food from time to
time, chemical objects which modify water status and of course
vegetals which provide Oxygen for our fishes.

As time passes some objects can start working badly or can
get too dirty so they may be removed and substitute or cleaned.

Fishes are files which are updated when they are in aquarium, while
they are not used they are kept in a fridge ( see @{"Frozen Fishes Directory" LINK "Frozen Fishes Directory" } )
where they are moved back when removed from aquaria.

Our goal is to keep alive our fishes and to enjoy their beauty
( gfx permitting ) for a long time.

This document is not complete as I wanted, sorry but I haven't
enough time to work on it. I should meet my prof on 14th June 1995
so I have to study for my exam ( and for others ), but please
if you have suggestions, critics, bugs informations tell me
I would appreciate very much also a simple usage message.
I tried to build a not-only-academic work and I hope that you
all enjoy it.

To know more about gadgets and MUI interface press the HELP
key while the mouse pointer is over the interesting gadget.

I can be reached at chieg@ghost.dsi.unimi.it

