@NODE "FishObj" "Manage Fishes And Objects"
Using Load Buttons and Remove Buttons you can add fishes and objects
into aquarium, then you can select them clicking with the left mouse
button on their name in the fish list or in the object list.
This lets you read information about energy of fishes or, when managing
objects, about their state (on/off), their production of O2 and CO2,
how old or dirty they are. In some cases you can open a settings window
which enables you to change the behaviour of these items, remember that
they need to be switched on to work correctly.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Change Water" "Change Water"
You can change old water deciding how much of it must be eliminated.
This is useful because lets you eliminate some toxic elements which
cannot be transormed ( NO3- ).

See @{"AQUAWC.prefs" LINK "AQUAWC.prefs" }

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Objects Infos" " Objects Infos "
There are many kind of objects:

Furnishings :
        These objects usually don't modify water characteristics
        and are used only to produce a nice visual effect
        ( Rock, Sand, ... )

Vegetals :
        These are algae and other vegetables which are very important
        since they produce oxygen during light hours so that our
        fishes can survive.

Chemical Objects :
        These objects should be used very carefully because they can
        alter concentration of elements in water; they should be used
        when we are in hurry to change some aspects which put our
        fishes in danger ( water hardness too low ... )

Food :
        This is a simple objects which is used simply to provide some
        food to fishes ( this can go bad and intoxicate water so
        be careful )

Other Objects :
        There are four kind of objects which can be very useful in
        aquarium maintenace :

        @{"Filter        " LINK "instr_filter" }
        @{"O2 Inhalator  " LINK "aqua_env_O2_txt" }
        @{"CO2 Inhalator " LINK "aqua_env_CO2_txt" }
        @{"Thermostat    " LINK "instr_thermo" }

See also how to write you objects and fishes in @{"Change System Updating" LINK "Changing System Updating" }
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Changing Updating Constants" "Changing Updating Constants"
@TOC "Changing System Updating"

Many of the constants used during system update can be redefined by
the user modifying 3 basic files:

The first is used when creating a new aquarium :

	@{"Startup.prefs" LINK "Startup.prefs" }

The other two are created in your aquarium directory and can
be modified by hand to change how the simulated aquarium
works :

	@{"AQUA.prefs   " LINK "AQUA.prefs" }
	@{"AQUAWC.prefs " LINK "AQUAWC.prefs" }

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Writing New Fishes" "Writing New Fishes"
@TOC "Changing System Updating"

You write a fish file by defining some important values, remember
that the file you're going to write should refer to a brand new
fish with maximum energy and born on the day you finished to
create it. Actually it will be moved to your aquarium directory
and will be rewritten from time to time to update its status.

NOTE: This also means you should always have a backup of your
fish data !

See an example of fish data file : @{"AngelFish.fsh" LINK "AngelFish.fsh" }

File names must end with .fsh

This must always be the first line AQUARIUM-FISH-DATA

If you don't have a picture for you fish, or you don't have a text ready
or if there is not a directory where to put your fish when you remove
it from your aquarium you should write ___ in the correspondant field.

Production of NH3 and NH4+ changes if fish is alive or if it's dead.

When concentration of elements in water doesn't respect fish needs
some energy points are subtracted, when these needs are respected
energy points are added, when energy level 0 is reached fish is dead.

See @{"Writing 3D File" LINK "3DFile" }
@ENDNODE

@NODE "AngelFish.fsh" "Angel Fish Example"
@TOC "Writing New Fishes"
AQUARIUM-FISH-DATA
Cichlids		# Race
Cichlids		# Subdirectory In AQUA:Frozen-Fishes/
			#  This Is Used To Replace Fish In Its Original
			#  Subdir When Removed From Aquarium
AngelFish.doc		# Information Text - Must Be In AQUA:Data/InfoDocs
AngelFish.iff		# Information Picture - Must Be In AQUA:Data/InfoPics
AngelFish.3do		# Graphic Data File - Must Be In AQUA:Data/3DObjs
0			# Sex -> 0 : Female  -  1 : Male
12			# Max Age In Years
22,4,1995		# Date Of Birth
0			# Age
0			# 0 : Fish Is Alive  -  1 : Fish Is Dead
0.010000		# Production Of CO2 And Consumption Of O2 Per Iteration
0.010000
0.001000		# Production Of NH3 And NH4+ When Alive P.I.
0.002000
0.0100000		# Production Of NH3 And NH4+ When Dead P.I.
0.0200000
100.000000		# Maximum CO2
1.000000		# Minimum O2
0.100000		# Maximum NH3 And NH4+
0.100000
10.000000		# Maximum NO2 And NO3-
200.000000
3.000000		# Water Hardness Range
4.000000
6.000000		# Ph Range
7.000000
22.000000		# Temperature Range
23.000000
1000			# Energy
0			# Hunger

@ENDNODE


@NODE "Writing New Objects" "Writing New Objects"
@TOC "Changing System Updating"

You write an object file by defining some important values, remember
that the file you're going to write should refer to a brand new
object with dirty and age set to zero create it.
Objects are not moved, like fishes, to your aquarium directory, they
are left in their original one and a simple copy of them is created
in your aquarium.
This copy will be rewritten from time to time to update object status.

See an example of object data file : @{"BasicFishTank.aqo" LINK "BasicFishTank.aqo" }

Object files must always end with .aqo

This must always be the first line AQUARIUM-FISH-DATA

If you don't have a picture for you object, or you don't have a text
ready should write ___ in the correspondant field.

Max production of an element usage depends on object:
For CO2 and O2 inhalator represent max production on CO2 or O2.
For food means how much food is provided at a time.
For Thermostat means max temperature selectable.

See @{"Writing 3D File" LINK "3DFile" }
@ENDNODE

@NODE "BasicFishTank.aqo" "Basic Fish Tank Object"
@TOC "Writing New Objects"
AQUARIUM-AQOBJ-DATA
___			# Info Text - Must Be In AQUA:Data/InfoDocs
___			# Info Picture - Must Be In AQUA:Data/InfoPics
fishtank.3do		# Graphic Data File - Must Be In AQUA:Data/3DObjs
301			# Kind Of Object See Below
0,0			# Object Switchable And Switch State ( Unused If
			#  Object Can't Be Switched On And Off, This Means
			#  That Object Is Always Chemically Active
0			# Age Of This Object In Iterations ( Not In Years As
			#  In Fish Age )
10			# Max Age : Max Number Of Iterations
0			# Autoremove : If 1 Means Object Is Removed When maxage
			#  Is Reached
0			# Dirty : How Dirty Is This Object ( Modifies Efficiency )
0			# Max Production Of An Element
			# (CO2 or O2 Producers / Thermostat / Food )
0,0			# Prod And Cons Of CO2
0,0			# Of O2
0,0			# Of NH3
0,0			# Of NH4+
0,0			# Of CACO3 Used For Calculate DH
0,0			# Alteration In PH
0			# Modification In Temperature Per Iteration
0			# Expected Temperature (for Thermostat)

#
# Object Kind Definition :
#
#	101		Furnishings
#	102		Vegetal
#	103		Chemical Element
#	104		Food
#
#	201		O2 Inalator
#	202		CO2 Inalator
#	203		Filter
#	204		Thermostat
#
#	301		Fish-Tank
#
#
#	Remember That Fish-Tank Is Always Present When An Aquarium Is Created
#

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Files" "File Management And AQUA: Structure"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
A directory will be used in which all file are grouped.
This directory is AQUA: and must be assigned to the directory
containing all the distribution.
Under AQUA: there will be other directories:

AQUA:

-> Data/
	This contains:

	->3DObjs/
		3D Object Data Files
	->InfoPics/
		Pictures of fishes and objects
	->InfoDocs/
		Text about fishes and objects
	->Palettes/
		Palette Data Files
	->FishesBackup.lha
		Backup Of Fishes Data ( only .fsh data files )

-> Frozen-Fishes/
	-> Cichlids/
		Fishes Of Cichlids Family

	-> .../ other families

	Fish Data Files

	NOTE: Each Subdir can contain other Fish Data Files

-> Objects/
	-> Furnishings/
		System non interactive objects

	-> Vegetals/
		Algae and similar

	-> Food/
		Food Objects

	-> Chemicals/
		Chemical Objects

	Other Kind of Object Files

-> Aquaria/

	This Directory will contain your aquarium and a file with
	the same aquarium name ending in .aqm with some aquarium data
	In your aquarium directory will be copied loaded objects, and
	will be moved loaded fishes.
	When yu remove a fish from aquarium it will be moved back
	to Frozen-Fishes directory ( or in a race subdir ).
	There are also two other files created in your aquarium dir:
	@{"AQUA.prefs" LINK "AQUA.prefs"} and @{"AQUAWC.prefs" LINK "AQUAWC.prefs" }

In the main thir there are AQUA main file and its icon, this guide
and eventually @{"Startup.prefs" LINK "Startup.prefs" }
@ENDNODE

@NODE "AQUA.prefs" "AQUA.prefs"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
This file contains some data which can be manually modified to change
the system updating behaviour.

The first 7 elements represent choices in preferences window and may
then better selected using it.

Then we have O2 and CO2 of external environment, these values are
used to move water O2 and CO2 to equilibrium and in water change
as values of O2 and CO2 in new water.

Next 11 values are used to define filter action:

First 3 values are thresholds saying when to produce bacteria,
the first is the amount needed of NH4+ which enables bacteria
production, the second is the NH3 threshold.
The third is the NO2 threshold which lets the system produce
some bacteria.
Bacteria of first kind (NH3/NH4) is different from the one
produced using NO2 threshold:
The first enable transformation of NH3 and NH4+ in NO2, the
second transforms NO2 in NO3-.

Next 2 values says how much NH3/NH4bacteria must be added
if respectively NH4+ and NH3 are above thresholds.
The same for next value which says how much NO2bacteria is
added when NO2 is above threshold.

Next 2 values define a maximum for NH3/NH4bacteria and for
NO2bacteria.

Next 2 values define how NH3/NH4bacteria eliminate respectively
NH3 and NH4+ considering how much bacteria is present and dirtiness
of filter, in practice this is a weight for the function which
transforms NH3 and NH4+ in NO2.

Next value is again a weight used in NO2 to NO3- transformation.

We have seen 20 values so far, now we have other 12 elements

First element defines energy points given when an element
concetration is in range or considered good in general.
The next one defines how many energy points are subtracted
when an element concentration is out of bounds.

NOTE: These values are considered for each element during
update.

NOTE: When you select Offset hit in preferences then above value
is not used because it depends on how much an element is
out of bounds and not only by the fact that it is out of bounds.

Then we have weights for different elements, this means that
when you select weighted hit following data is used to compute
how many energy points we should subtract from fish energy.

We have the last 10 items which mean respectively weights for:
Fish Hunger   ( This is not explained but if a fish is very
		hunger it influences energy )
O2 out of bounds
CO2
NH3
NH4+
NO2
NO3-
DH
PH
Temperature

NOTE: Total number of items should be : 32

@ENDNODE

@NODE "AQUAWC.prefs" "AQUAWC.prefs"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"

Changing new water elements concentration modifying AQUAWC.prefs
file in your aquarium directory ( in AQUA:Aquaria dir )

In this file you can find 3 elements which are :
New water temperature,
New water hardness (DH)
New water Ph

Fix these values to your needs but don't put values needed by your
fishes because this doesn't happen in true life, for example don't
say water temp is 22°C because this is not real usually, say for
example that new water temperature is 10 or 12 °C, this is better
and forces you to use a Thermostat.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Startup.prefs" "Startup.prefs"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"

If you don't like starting values of your aquaria you can create
your own starting values ( used by all new aquaria ) saving
a file named -> Startup.prefs <- in directory AQUA:

Startup.prefs should have this format:
Each value separated by new lines, 12 values, if you don't know
or you don't want to change some of the default values, put
___ in the desired place

Values means, in this order, starting values for :
					   Default Values
O2						5.0
CO2						2.0
NH3						0.0
NH4+						0.0
NO2						0.0
NO3-						0.0
CACO3				      35.8 ( it means 2.0 Dh )
Ph						7.0
Dh						2.0
Temperature					10.0
bacteria which transform NH3/NH4+ in NO2	0.0 ( < 1.5 )
bacteria which transform NO2 in NO3		0.0 ( < 11.0 )


@ENDNODE

@NODE "3DFile" "Writing 3D File"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
If you want to make a fish or an object ( usually furnishings and 
vegetals ) you may decide to add some gfx to see it in you aquarium.
As said in @{"Writing New Objects" LINK "Writing New Objects" } you should not write
gfx for food and chemical objects, since they're used only to change
water situation or to provide some food to your fishes in a short
period of time.

A 3d data file is located in AQUA:Data/3DObjs and can be loaded by
more than a fish ( more fishes of the same kind ) or more than a
object ( this is bit different see below ); its name ends with
the .3do suffix.

We'll study a simple example the @{"Sand.3do" LINK "Sand.3do" }

The first line must always be 3DSYSDATA-OBJ which tells the
loader that this is a 3d data file.

As you can see there are a lot of #s around, these characters
are used to introduce till-end-of-line-remarks, so that you
can comment your files.
Then we have number of frames; since our objects can be animated
you must give here the number of frames which build animation.
Remember every data complex data starts from index 0, so, in
animation case, if we have a 3 frames animated object first
animation frame would have been number 0.
In Sand.3do we have a non-animated ( 1 Frame Object ) so
we have 1 in number of frames field.

NOTE: you can separate different fields with commas "," or
with newline, and you can put spaces or tabs to separate
fields; empty new lines are skipped.

Now lets look at the frame structure :
0, 14, 0, 0, 0, 1
a  b   c  d  e  f

a = Offset in array of all points ( all frame points sequentially )
b = Number of points for this frame
c = Offset in array of lines
d = Number of lines for this frame
e = Offset in array of surfaces
f = Number of surfaces for this frame

This can be hard to understand I try to be as clear as I can :
You draw you object on paper and you made many drawings ( one
for each frame ) then you number each vertex in each frame
starting from 0 : this means that we have a 0 vertex in frame
one, a 0 vertex in frame two and so on, after we'll look
on how to build lines and surfaces with this data but for
now we fix the fact that we'll use vertex numbering relative
to each frame in building lines and surfs too.

Now we put together all points we have written on paper writing
first of all points of frame 0 then points of frame 1 and so on,
just one point after another from 0 to numpoints-1, one frame
after another from 0 to numframes-1.
When I say we write points I mean we write their coordinates
in this order : X, Y, Z
If you like you can group data using { and } which are simply
skipped ( since a single number is a data item you should put
a comma "," after Z if you want to start another point on
the same line ).
After we have written ALL object POINTS we count them and
we put this number before the first point, this is the
array of points dimension.

Now we can try to understand what "Offset in array of all points"
means in "a" above. A single frame is found by reading its
points data, and to do so we load ALL object POINTS at a time
we keep them together and we build a single frame by starting
not from the first point but from the first point plus offset,
how to calculate this offset ? Simple, first frame start at
the beginning of the array, so offset is 0, the second frame
starts from last offset plus the number of points of the last
frame.
In Sand.3do we have a single frame but if we want to add a new
one we should say 2 in number of frames data and add a line
with 14 as offset ( 0 old offset + 14 num points of old frame )
and, for example, 12 points, this also means that total number
of point will be 26 ( 14 first frame + 12 second frame ).

I hope it is all clearer now ( read again if you don't understand ).

Now we have number of elements in sequence.

Again, think we have 3 frames, frame 0, 1 and 2.
How do we say when to show one and when another ?
Simply specifying order in sequence, but before we must say how long
this sequence is.
In Sand we have a single frame so sequence is 1 frame long and frame
to be shown is always frame 0.

NOTE:
We show a frame after the other respecting sequence data but at the
of it we start back from frame number one ( the first frame specified
in sequence ) and we DO NOT repeat sequence in the opposite direction.
So if we want to perform a so called Ping Pong animation ( useful when
moving a fin from one side to another ) we should make a longer sequence.
Example : frames are 0-1-2 ( 3 frames ) and we want to show them this
way : 0 1 2 1 0 1 2 1 0 1 2 1 ...
If we simply write seq length 3 and sequence : 0 1 2 we'll get an
animation of this kind : 0 1 2 0 1 2 0 1 2
So we must say :
seq length = 4 ( usually -> old seq_length + old seq_length - 2 )
and sequence = 0 1 2 1
this will produce the right animation.

Ok...lets try to go on...
Now we have TOTAL object POINTS number  ( ALL FRAMES CONSIDERED
see above ) and then points data:
As I've already said each point is made of 3 numbers ( each positive
or negative ) and if you want to put more than a point on the
same line you shold put a comma after each Z.

Then we have TOTAL object LINES number, again lines are put
together in a single array and frame offset tells the system where
to get the current frame lines in it.
Now we have all lines needed in animation:
in Sand there are not lines but line format is
a, b, c, ....
so three elements which are a : line color, b : starting point
c : ending point.
These point are relative to the current frame, do you remember
what I said before, we'll build lines and surfaces using points
numeration relative to each frame, so if in frame zero we have
a line which start from point 0 and ends in point 4, and in frame
three another line which starts from point 0 and point 4 we should
not replicate them because we already changed points and since
points numbering is relative to current frame we may say that
points are changed in position but connections are not, so there
is always a line ( or a surface as we'll see ) connecting the
"same" ( as numbers ) points but the points are now different
because we loaded different points in the array using frame
points offset.
This means that often we can define lines and surfaces for a
single frame ( usually frame 0 ) and then we can just rewrite
different points for each frame, but since connection are not
changed because there is a line in each frame wich links point
0 to point 4 ( for example ) we'll see a line in each frame.
How to do so ? Simply specifying offset 0 in lines ( or surfaces )
offset for each frame, this forces the system to reload always
the same data which always says to connect the same points
but since point 0 will not be always the same we have lines
which follows points.
Example: a 3 frame object with 5 points each frame and with
2 lines and 1 surface in each frame.
0, 5, 0, 2, 0, 1
a  b  c  d  e  f
a = offset ( 0 ) start from array beginning
b = 5 points for frame 0
c = offset 0 start from line array beginning
d = 2 lines
e = offset 0 start from surfs array beginning
f = 1 surface

now frame 1:
5, 5, 0, 2, 0, 1
a  b  c  d  e  f
a = offset 5 = start from position 5 in array ( points are different )
b = load 5 points
c = offset 0 = will reload old lines data
d = again 2 lines
e = offset 0 = will reload old surface data
f = again same surface

frame 2:
10, 5, 0, 2, 0, 1

Again points will be loaded in another position and we can suppose
they will be different, but lines and surfaces connect the same
points number so 0 is just a name to define the first point loaded
which can be in frame 0 : 3,4,5 , but in frame 2 it can be : -4,3,2.
Using relative and not absolute data helps in building objects.

Now we can see TOTAL object SURFACES number and surfaces:
In Sand.3do there is only one surface:

6, 4,	{0,2,3,1},	5,	
0,5,6,	0,8,9,	0,11,12,	
0,4,10,	0,7,13
0

the first element is the surface color number, the second
tells the number of vertexes which make up the surface
between { and } ( which are not considered )
there is the vertex list: 0,2,3,1 this are the vertex readed
anti-clockwise which build surface ( of course if you have
a surface wich is made of more than 3 vertexes you should
be sure that they are complanar or strange things may appear
during drawing ).
Then you must define the number of lines which will be
drawn over this surface when it is visible.
In Sand they are 5.
Then we have lines whose points refer to the current frame
points bnumber.
Last value is used to tell the system if we should only
draw lines when surface is visible ( 1 ) or if we should
draw both ( 0 ) surface first and lines then.

Now we have the name of this object, this is not used
at the moment since the name is derived from the master
fish or object file name.

NOTE: Name should end with a new line since also spaces
are considered.

Center of the object, this point in space is used to move
objects and to derive insersection information among all
objects; if you distribute your points around the axis
and zero goes in the middle of your object you can usually
define 0,0,0 as center for fishes, this means that they
are placed in the middle of the fishtank when they start
moving, for non fish objects, it can be useful to move
an item in a particular place.
For example Sand object is defined as a surface with some
lines above it, and the center of the surface is 0,-30,0
this point put the surface on the bottom of our fishtank
which is large as all "swimmable" space, this could also
be done defining all points data with -30 Y, but using
again relative positioning of objects it is more clearer
to define objects relative to 0,0,0 center and then move
them to fix them on the bottom or in another place.

NOTE: Space through which fishes can swim is defined as a
box of width 120, height 60 and depth 60 and since center
of it is 0,0,0 value of points X,Y and Z should be :
axis	 min 	max	Front View Object Orientation
 X	-60	60	left - right
 Y	-30	30	bottom - top
 Z	-30	30	front - rear

Front View Object Orientation means what you see when using
a negative and a positive value, so for X axis if you define
a negative value in X coordinate in a point you are defining
something on the left side of the screen if you look the
object from the defined starting point of view.

NOTE: It was said before that you should define a surface
specifying points indexes in anti-clockwise order, this
means that you shoulde look at a surface staying in front
at it and that looking at its points, so if in your drawing
the base of a pyramid is to be defined and your drawing
show this object in perspective you should remember to
see the base from the bottom or from under the paper and
this means that anti-clockwise order should be the opposite
of what it seems looking from natural position.

NOTE: Another suggestion about surfaces :
If you want to make things such as fins with a single surface
or in any case you're defining surfaces that don't contain
volume of space you should remember that more than a surface
is needed, one surface which appears when looked from one side
on the other side disappears, so it is necessary to put
another mirrored surface on the other side so that one
disappears another appears and nothing seems changed.
To do so simply define another surface with the same vertexes
in opposite order.
In Sand our surface disappear when you look from the bottom
of the aquarium, but this is what we want or we couldn't see
anything, to make a double-face surface in this case we could
put another definition ( without lines for simplicity ) which
looks like this :
6, 4,	{3,2,0,1},	0,0	# Last 2 Numbers means 0 lines
				# over surface and no transparent
				# surface

We could have said {1,3,2,0} but sometimes it happens that
near points or points which stay almost on a line get calculated
in a wrong way, so it is better to use the same three points
in a reverse order when we saw that they worked well in the first
surface.

NOTE: To check if a surface is visible or not from a certain point
of view only the first 3 points ( which are enough to define a
surface ) are used so there is not checking for complanar points.
This can be useful so that even not complanar vertexes surfaces are
drawn but check for the result first ( It can be useful because
you can define only one surface instead of breaking it in many
trangles or other surfaces made up of perfectly compolanar vertexes ).

NOTE: I didn't tell you but elements are all Integers, not in floating
point format.

Going on we found data defining how to scale our objects
these three values refer to X, Y and Z axes and are in tenth
of our unit, so if your object is already scaled when you have
drawn it on paper ( this is better ) you should declare 10,10,10
for scale factors.

Now you can decide if you object should move ( always for
fishes ) specifying 1 or if your object must remain in its
original position specifying 0.
Again a boolean value for solid objects :
Solid objects are automatically avoided by other objects
so our fishtank is non solid because fishes should swim in
it, fishes are solid, algae should be solid if very big
leaves are drawn, and so on...
Other simple elements can be non solid so that fishes or other
moving objects can pass through them.
Last flag, visible, should always be 1 or you wouldn't see
you object ( and after all the work needed to draw it, it
wouldn't be a great idea in my opinion ;)

Now some theory before going on ( and finishing...puff :)
Every object is enclosed in a box centered in object's
center ( ! ), this box is never rotated ( and this is a
limitation see below :( ) but it's translated to follow
object's center and so object's movements.
This box represents the volume occupied by our object and
every intersection checing is made using this box.

This box can be a cube so the auto bounding box flag must
be set to 1, in this case the next number will be the side
of the cube divided by two ( the half side in another words ).
This half side is used adding it to the center of the object
everytime space consumption is calculated.
If you need to be more precise because you object is not
so simmetrical you can put 0 in the bounding box flag and
then specify sides of a box considering negative and positive
sides separately.
For example our Sand.3do is simmetrical around the center
along each axis but a cube would have wasted a lot of space
because sand is practically flat and so 0,0 are the half
sides along Y axis.
Each axis has two numbers associated because you must say
how much space is occupied in the two directions used, first
the negative one and then the positive.

REM: So if you say 1 in flag you only specify ONE value
after, the half side of the bounding cube, if you say 0
in the flag you must provide 6 values.

Now we have finished, we need to explain only the last number
This number is used to set the priority in sorting elements
before drawing, it must be practivally always 0, but since Sand
is very simmetric along z axis it may be drawn after other objects
which may be swimming far from the center of our virtual space
and be far away from our point of view, so to prevent Sand
to be drawn after this objects we give it a priority of 1
saying we want it to be drawn before any other object.

NOTE: In practice nearer objects are drawn after far away ones,
but very simmetrical and full-space-occupying objects can
be drawn before others even when this not true so this flag
was necessary to create a priority in drawing ( in practice
you should never use one because Sand should be the only
object which could have had this kind of problem ).

I hope this can help you in making wonderful new fishes and
other piece of furnishings, see @{"Copyright" LINK "Copyright" } and @{ "Author" LINK "Author" } for
contacting me and distribute your work ( or for further
explanation ;)

Good Work!

See Also @{" File Management And AQUA: Structure" LINK "Files" }
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Sand.3do" "A 3D File Example Sand.3do"
@TOC "3DFile"
3DSYSDATA-OBJ
#
#
#   Sand Object - By Giuseppe Chiesa Feb 1995
#
#
1               	# Number Of Frames
0,14,0,0,0,1		# Frames
1			# Number Of Elements In Sequence
0			# Sequence 
14			# Number Of Points
-60,0,30,	60,0,30
-60,0,-30,	60,0,-30
-20,0,10,	40,0,-16
2,0,-30,	-2,0,30
-10,0,-20,	10,0,10
-28,0,-8,	-4,0,-2
26,0,0,		16,0,20
0			# Number Of Lines
1			# Number Of Surfaces
# Surfaces - Color 1 Is Transparent
6, 4,	{0,2,3,1},	5,	# ( 5 = ) Number Of Lines O.S.
0,5,6,	0,8,9,	0,11,12,	# Lines Over Surface
0,4,10,	0,7,13
0				# Transparent Surf Off
# Name
Sand
0,-30,0             # Center
10,10,10            # Scale Factors Along Axes
0,0,1               # Movable, Solid Visible
0		    # Auto Bounding Box Flag
60,60               # Bounding Box Radius
0,0
30,30
1
@ENDNODE

