@NODE "Menus" "Menu"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"

Aquarium Simulator has a single menu :

- Project
	- About                Some information about me and Aqua Sim
	- Open                 Load a saved aquarium
	- Save                 Save current aquarium ( if created or loaded )
	- New                  Create a new aquarium
	- Preferences          Open preferences window

- Misc
	- @{"Automation Prefs" LINK "Automation Prefs"}     Open automation preferences window
	- @{"Change Water" LINK "Change Water" }         Change water in aquarium
	- Show Names           Switch to anim screen and show names of objects
                                and fishes

- Animation ( See @{"Animation Screen" LINK "Animation Screen" } )
	- Change Screen        Change screen mode
	- Change Palette       Change Palette


@ENDNODE

@NODE "changelight_txt" "Auto Light Switcher Countdown"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
This number represent how many iterations are need for light state to be
changed, if on it goes off, if off it goes on.
This works when Autolight switcher is on in @{"Automation Prefs" LINK "Automation Prefs" }

@ENDNODE

@NODE "hunger_ga" "Hunger Gauge"
@TOC "Aquarium Simulator"
This gauge simply shows fish hunger, don't let it go over 80 or your fish
will lose some energy points because of that.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "FINSReadme" "FINS Info"
@TOC "MAIN"

These pictures are offered as a free information service.  They are
here for individuals to use, but please do not redistribute them
without contacting me first.

The collection is still growing, and we're trying to get better
quality pictures.  I expect it to take several months before the
archive is really in shape.  If you access them through WWW at
"http://www.actwin.com/fish", they are indexed by scientific name,
common name and type of fish, and have the photo credits attached.
This is the preferred way for people to view these pictures.


Photo Credits

These are either taken by Mark Rosenstein or Jaison Laird on video,
and are either of our aquariums or from the Boston pet stores Big
Fish, Little Fish and Boston Pet Center.  They were shot on Hi-8
video, digitized, then retouched in photoshop.  The color balance may
seem off because I've found that different platforms (i.e. Macs and
Unix) display them very differently.  I'm working on some ways to
improve the quality, though I want to keep the images small so that
they can be downloaded quickly.


Mark Rosenstein
mar@actwin.com
9/18/94

@ENDNODE

